<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO DOC</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 16  7:10:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc,<br><br>
The *one time* I have addressed the issue of racial slurs was in the above post to John Ratliff. My point was to reassure him that he was correct in feeling offended - as his wife is Asian.<br><br>
I used a variation of racial name for the Vietnamese - not just the enemy - while I was serving in their country. I don't use it today, and would certainly not attempt to justify using any derogatory words in my writing, that is, unless I was quoting someone. <br><br>
Having said this, I don't feel strongly enough about the issue to accuse people like Cook of being a racist. Cook's name is ethnic sounding, you are Jewish, Arthur is Italian, my mother is Italian, Edward is Native American. We all have been targets of epithets. There is no denying that each of us has at least a small amount of prejudice. No?<br><br>
If we make a habit of using these words in our writing, the people who read them are sophisticated enough to decide whether the writings are racially motivated. I respect your opinion, but it is time to move past this issue with this: people who use words which have the potential of being viewed as racist, do so at their own risk.<br>
 <br>
As for serving in vain, I disagree. Sometimes our journey doesn't always arrive at the desired destination. Not accomplishing what we set out to do does not rule out the fact that great things were accomplished. Our mission as Americans is not finished.<br><br>
Of course many prefer to leave the Vietnam War on the scrapheap of the past. Others of us choose to use it as something to build upon. This dialogue is proof. Our mission should be one of reconciliation - reversing the polarization that has its roots in the turmoil of the 1960's. That is our nation's biggest threat today. Stubborn partisanship. We have a tremendous opportunity, as people who lived during those times to do something about it.
<p><code>-- *wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


